\f1\b0 ) is a\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Buddhism"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 Buddhist}}\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monastery"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 monastery}}\'a0located in the remote Lungnak Valley in south-eastern\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zanskar"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 Zanskar}}, in the\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Himalaya"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 Himalayan}}\'a0region of\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ladakh"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 Ladakh}}, in\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Northern_India"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 Northern India}}. It is one of the only Buddhist monasteries in Ladakh that can still be reached only by foot. Supplies to the monastery are brought on horses, donkeys, and mules in the warmer months, and in the frozen winters, they are transported through the frozen\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zanskar_River"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 Zanskar River}}. A road is expected to be built up to the monastery, however, for now, it is a day's walk from Village Cha or Village Khangsaar, the end of the road leading from\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Padum"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 Padum}}.\
