\cf2 The Phuktal Monastery is built around a natural cave, which is believed to have been visited by numerous sages, scholars, translators, and monks around 2,550 years ago. The remote location of the monastery was ideal for monks looking for peace and solitude to meditate. The present Phuktal Gompa, of the\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gelug"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 Gelug}}\'a0school of\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tibetan_Buddhism"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 Tibetan Buddhism}}, was established in the early 15th century by\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jangsem_Sherap_Zangpo"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 Jangsem Sherap Zangpo}}, a disciple of Je Tsongkhapa. Tsongkhapa was the founder of Gelug, which is one of the newest schools of Tibetan Buddhism.\
Believed to be one of the earliest residents of the cave are the\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sixteen_Arhats"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 16 Arhats}}, or the legendary followers of\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Buddha"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 Buddha}}. The images of these 16\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arhats"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 Arhats}}\'a0appear on the cave walls. The great scholars and translators\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Padmasambhava"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 Padmasambhava}}\'a0and Phakspa Nestan Dusdan are believed to have lived in the cave, and so is the great leader and translator\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marpa_Lotsawa"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 Lama Marpa Lotsawa}}. In the 12th century, the Tibetan translator Zanskar Lotsawa Phagpa Sherab also lived and worked from Phuktal. The eminent scholars and brothers Dangsong, Pun, and Sum, who were believed to have the supernatural power of flight gave teachings on\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dharma"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 Dharma}}\'a0at Phuktal. When Jangsem Sherap Zangpo arrived at Phuktal, the three brothers bequeathed the holy site to him and departed. According to legend, the spiritually gifted Zangpo caused a spring to appear and run from the cave, a tree to grow on top of the cave and for the cave itself to grow larger in size. Then, under his guidance, the present structure of the monastery was built around the cave. It is built in the cliffside, like a honeycomb. The cliff is part of a lateral gorge of a major tributary of the Lungnak River (Lingti-{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tsarap_River"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 Tsarap}}\'a0River). The monastery today houses a main temple, prayer rooms, a library with rare sacred texts, apartments and living quarters, teaching facilities, a kitchen, and of course, the original cave and the sacred spring, which is protected. It is home to about 70 monks\
